ite automaton</keyword><keyword weight="0.61458">Mobile automaton</keyword><keyword weight="0.65646">Nested word</keyword><keyword weight="0.45932">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.61475">Deterministic finite automaton</keyword><keyword weight="0.46337">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.60226">Timed automaton</keyword><keyword weight="0.66192">Ï‰-automaton</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Finite automata have two traditional applications in computer science: modeling of finite-state systems and description of regular set of finite words. In the last few years, several new applications for finite-state automata have emerged, e.g., optimization of logic programs and specification and verification of protocols. These applications use finite-state automata to describe regular sets of infinite words and trees. I will describe such applications and will argue that we need change the way we teach automata theory.</abstract></paper>